My blunt read: Programme-3 has built an unusually good machine for preventing self-deception, but it is in danger of becoming an evaluation-and-governance programme with a neurosymbolic experiment attached. The architecture portfolio is too broad relative to how little evidence currently survives the full path from real input to matched-baseline advantage.

## 1. What is going well, what is going poorly, and the biggest risk

Going well:

- The epistemic hygiene is excellent. The programme openly distinguishes exactness on a self-authored formal substrate from usefulness on real input. That is rare and valuable.
- The exact engine is genuinely good engineering: sound, fail-closed, portable across two verticals, and microsecond-cheap.
- The G1→G5 ladder is basically right. Oracle-interface gains are quarantined, natural-language degradation is explicit, and the neural/RAG frontier is treated as something to build rather than straw-man.
- The corrected measurement designs are strong. In particular, the resource-vector frontier, aligned-non-kernel controls, generic-RAG cells, oracle splice ladder, and corrected coverage bound substantially reduce the chance of claiming a fake win. [Programme design](</home/ec2-user/css/kernel/kernel-of-truth/docs/next/programme-3-neurosymbolic-architecture.md>) [Frontier design](</home/ec2-user/css/kernel/kernel-of-truth/docs/next/design/FRONT.md>) [Oracle decomposition](</home/ec2-user/css/kernel/kernel-of-truth/docs/next/design/ORACLE.md>)
- The programme has correctly learned that delivery is not use, execution validity is not semantic correctness, attention is not provenance, and a correct checker cannot repair a wrong formalization.

Going poorly:

- There is still no kernel-content-attributable end-task win. The one promising efficiency result is alignment-specific and could be reproduced by a generic aligned answer-key/store. The formal a5 win lacks the conventional typed-store/executor control that matters.
- The programme is spreading scarce attention over too many speculative families before resolving the two existential questions: can the store cover enough valuable cases, and can real language safely address it?
- The documentation and measurement superstructure are now far ahead of the experimental evidence. FRONT, MF0, ORACLE, and POWER are sophisticated, but the corrected POWER result explicitly withdrew the apparent live coverage kill because the index census is incomplete. The programme has designed a decisive gate without yet supplying its decisive inputs.
- “Kernel of Truth” is drifting toward “generic typed store plus exact executor.” That may still be a useful system, but it is a different scientific claim. The programme has controls for this distinction; it has not prioritised their execution strongly enough.
- The full multi-domain AI index is premature as the main battlefield. With present coverage, broad averaging mainly guarantees dilution. A sharp domain-vector result in code/tools/schemas would teach more than a weak scalar across six domains.

The single biggest risk is attribution collapse: after paying for coverage, parsing, retrieval, abstention, maintenance, and integration, the kernel-specific semantics add no marginal value over a strong generic typed-store/tool-RAG system using the same source material and executor. The current evidence points uncomfortably in that direction: the only end-task sign is alignment-confounded, while literature wins mostly come from external execution, retrieval, training, or structured interfaces—not from a privileged semantic kernel.

The coverage and NL walls make this risk worse, but attribution collapse is the deepest one: even solving those walls may merely produce a good conventional tool-using system.

## 2. Most and least promising architectural directions

### Most promising

1. Selective contract front-end + ambiguity-set execution

This is P1/M1+K2+W3, and it is the most important experiment—not because it is likely to become a universal parser, but because it directly attacks the measured failure.

The strongest version is:

- learned canonical utterance/DSL parser;
- explicit inverse and role alternatives;
- execute the whole calibrated ambiguity set;
- answer only when denotations agree;
- deterministic templates for rendering wherever possible;
- clarify or abstain otherwise.

The ambiguity-set executor is especially good. It attacks valid-but-wrong direction flips, which ordinary execution-guided parsing cannot detect. Contracts alone are insufficient because correlated or systematically inverted parses can be self-consistent. [PARSE review](</home/ec2-user/css/kernel/kernel-of-truth/docs/next/lit/PARSE.md>) [Round-1 synthesis](</home/ec2-user/css/kernel/kernel-of-truth/docs/next/arch/round1-critique-synthesis.md>)

2. Executor-coupled, span-scoped constrained decoding in structured domains

P3/M2/H-RULE-CD is the best integration mechanism. It has the strongest in-band literature support, asks the model to consume engine-derived results rather than execute rules internally, and exploits the engine’s genuinely unusual microsecond cost.

The credible wedge is code, tool calls, schemas, configuration, and other syntax-grounded domains. Apply masks only where addressing is certain; leave reasoning and uncovered spans unconstrained; preserve refusal; compare directly against post-hoc verify-retry on the complete resource vector.

This is much more promising than putting rules into weights or activations. [RULE review](</home/ec2-user/css/kernel/kernel-of-truth/docs/next/lit/RULE.md>)

3. Deterministic extraction as a feeder for the same structured-domain wedge

P7 is not an architecture, but it is strategically essential. Code structure, type signatures, schemas, and genuinely structured tables are the only plausible route to simultaneously improving coverage, reducing authoring cost, and making addressing less ambiguous.

This should not be generalized prematurely to prose, infobox labels, or arbitrary knowledge graphs. Deterministic extraction is not deterministic semantic typing.

4. Verifier-loop as incumbent, not as the visionary bet

H-VL/P5 remains the current empirical incumbent because it has the only end-task-shaped positive. But until the aligned-non-kernel ablation reads out, it is evidence for “cheap exact aligned verification,” not for Kernel-of-Truth semantics. Keep it as the comparator the more integrated system must beat.

5. Claim firewall as a cheap diagnostic

P2/K3 is worth its oracle ceiling census because subclaim coverage might exceed whole-query coverage. But it should not be promoted to an architecture until abstention scoring is frozen and extraction agreement is calibrated against human semantic gold. Two extractors agreeing is not soundness.

### Low-priority or likely dead ends

- H-DD / “drop 80% of dimensions and backfill from the store”: likely dead. Superposition, unstable SAE features, localization failures, worse small-model pruning retention, and the absence of any demonstrated concept-to-parameter correspondence all cut against it. At most run the cheap causal gate if it truly costs little; do not fund the pruning programme unless selective ablation and store-specific restoration are spectacular. [SURG review](</home/ec2-user/css/kernel/kernel-of-truth/docs/next/lit/SURG.md>)
- H-RULE-ACT activation steering: effectively a dead end for primary investment. The literature is predominantly negative at the relevant scale, prompting often wins, and the programme already measured delivery without demonstrated use.
- Rule-as-adapter and model editing: dead as rule channels. Adapters may teach consult/format/defer behaviour around an executor; they should not be treated as a sound rule store.
- H-RULE-HL/concept bottlenecks: defer indefinitely. Expensive, leakage-prone, and unsupported relative to shallower placements.
- KV-of-rules: likely dead. KV-of-engine-derived facts is at least coherent; KV-of-rule-premises merely moves the composition problem into a host that has weak evidence for latent composition.
- Full GNN→LM fusion: weak bet. The literature review found no fully matched, structure-causal win; gains shrink sharply once the host receives comparable adaptation, and perturbation evidence suggests some systems mostly read text. Retain one cheap, well-controlled size×depth sweep if desired, but expect the null. Deterministic graph traversal or graph retrieval is more credible than learned graph-token fusion. [FUSE review](</home/ec2-user/css/kernel/kernel-of-truth/docs/next/lit/FUSE.md>)
- Routed symbolic-expert MoE/P6: intellectually interesting, but late and speculative. It repeats the unresolved delivery-to-use seam and adds expensive training/accounting. Do not run it until capsule transfer, causal field perturbation, and learned-addressing tests are positive.
- Bitemporal hypergraph/W1: defer. It is GraphRAG-adjacent infrastructure with high extraction and lifecycle costs, not a first-wave mechanism.
- Compiled materialized views/W2: dead at current scale. There is no measured reuse-heavy workload and the existing engine is already microsecond-fast.
- Cascade/escalation routing: already dead at scope.
- Differentiable logic inside the host: deprioritize. The matched record is poor, grounding and scaling are bad, and external execution has much stronger evidence.

## 3. What to change immediately

I would freeze most of the portfolio and run the following sequence.

1. Repair and rerun the deterministic ROLE_DIR failure immediately.

This is not a research project. It is a table bug plus exhaustive both-orientation tests. No learned parser experiment should begin on top of a known defective semantic table.

2. Run the kernel-specific attribution kill before more architecture work.

Execute the aligned-non-kernel/plain typed-store ablation against H-VL. If a generic aligned store plus the same retry/executor semantics reproduces the gain, stop calling the result kernel-content evidence. The human f2b-transfer adjudication is also valuable, but the cheap aligned-store control should not wait.

This is more decisive than another architecture survey.

3. Complete the coverage census on the actual target suites and chosen domain wedge.

POWER is not currently a live whole-programme kill: the corrected result says exactly that. Finish the oracle/upper-sieve census, covered-subset baseline accuracies, and lifecycle cost of reaching required κ. Compute the joint upper bound:

`coverage × baseline-error headroom × boundary survival × mechanism efficacy`

The programme currently reasons about these pieces separately; their product is the real feasibility number.

4. Run the front-end seam test before training the parser.

Gold DSL → execution → deterministic template rendering should be nearly perfect. If templates suffice, delete the learned renderer from round one. A learned renderer creates a needless second NL boundary and is already cautioned by the net-harmful text-delivery result.

5. Make the learned NLB experiment the dominant next-wave spend.

Use real held-out human phrasings, not mainly programme-generated paraphrases. Include:

- disjoint author/source splits;
- both orientations of every directional frame;
- ambiguity and unanswerable inputs;
- distribution-shift perturbations;
- confidence-only, contracts, hard negatives, and ambiguity-set execution arms;
- clarification as an explicit action, not only answer/abstain;
- full risk–coverage curves.

If this fails two properly distinct redesigns, accept that general-NL Kernel-of-Truth is dead at this scale. Do not invent a fourth parser cycle.

6. In parallel, run P3 vs P5 on the formal/code slice.

Compare symbolic speculative decoding against verify-retry with accuracy and dangerous-wrong non-inferiority plus a material latency/token/resource improvement. This is the cleanest architectural experiment tied to the strongest evidence.

7. Drop or park now:

- active H-DD development beyond its causal kill;
- ACT, rule-editing, rule-as-adapter, and HL;
- hypergraph construction;
- GNN fusion beyond one bounded falsifier;
- generic parallel H-GU variants;
- materialized views;
- any new architecture-family ideation.

8. Concentrate the programme on one wedge.

My choice is code/tool/schema/configuration tasks with deterministically extracted worlds and syntax-grounded execution. Demonstrate a hard matched win there first. Only then attempt prose-heavy general knowledge.

What is missing:

- A clearly chosen deployment workload. The current broad index is an evaluation instrument, not a product hypothesis.
- Real-user or independently authored NL data and an interactive clarification policy.
- The generic typed-store + generic executor baseline as a first-class scientific rival, not merely one factorial cell.
- A stopping rule for kernel-specific semantics. If the aligned-non-kernel store repeatedly matches it, rename/re-scope the project.
- More human annotation execution and less design expansion. The capstone itself says the binding constraints are human/input work and one cheap ablation, not compute.
- A direct analysis of whether the required store can fit the resource budget at the κ needed to move the index. “Coverage can be grown” is meaningless without bytes and authoring cost.
- A positive-value treatment of abstention/clarification. Selectivity is probably the architecture’s advantage, but the scalar index still risks either rewarding abstention for free or punishing it into irrelevance.

## 4. Is it attacking the NL wall hard enough?

In design terms, yes. In resource allocation and experimental urgency, no.

The programme now has excellent NL-boundary governance: NLB gates every natural store leg, oracle gains are quarantined, ORACLE can localize losses, H-PS/P1 is first-class, and the programme has a quantitative kill after two redesigns.

But much of the portfolio is still building around the wall:

- GNN, capsule, DD, GU, and symbolic-expert work begins on oracle addresses.
- Formal/code wins are discussed as architecture signals while the natural-input leg remains absent.
- The oracle decomposition makes failures intelligible but does not make the boundary better.
- Deterministic extraction improves ingestion, not NL query addressing.
- Abstention can make the system safe while leaving it too low-coverage to beat RAG.

The current plan treats NLB as one workstream that gates the others. It should be treated as the main architectural experiment, receiving most of the next wave’s attention. The literature gives a legitimate reason for optimism—the failed parser was almost comically weak, and the paraphrase failure is probably method-limited—but it does not establish the joint ≥0.90 retention plus dangerous-wrong gate. The direction-error residue may remain stubborn even after ordinary exact-match accuracy improves.

My strongest advice is not “solve unrestricted NL.” It is: choose the narrowest high-value domain where syntax, deterministic extraction, ambiguity-set execution, and clarification make the boundary tractable, then demand a matched end-to-end win there.

Single most promising direction: a structured-domain selective coprocessor—deterministic extraction, learned contract front-end producing an ambiguity set, exact execution, and span-scoped symbolic speculative decoding or bounded verify-retry.

Top thing to change: stop broadening the portfolio and spend the next wave on the aligned-generic-store deconfound, complete coverage arithmetic, and the real held-out NLB gate.

Biggest risk: the kernel’s distinctive semantics contribute nothing beyond what a generic typed store, executor, and strong tool/RAG baseline already provide.